          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow and Friday, ba=
ck on Monday, and there will be no Money Stuff podcast this week. Happy Ind=
ependence Day!

 =20
   =20
      Regulation by enforcement
   =20
 =20

It might be=C2=A0impossible=C2=A0for the US Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion to write new rules for crypto? We have talked, over the years, about ho=
w the crypto industry frequently says that it wants the SEC (or the Commodi=
ty Futures Trading Commission, or Congress) to write rules regulating crypt=
ocurrency markets, so that the industry can have regulatory clarity and get=
 on with building the future of finance or whatever. Instead, crypto people=
 complain, there is =E2=80=9Cregulation by enforcement=E2=80=9D: Rather tha=
n writing clear rules saying what is allowed, the SEC just decides on a cas=
e-by-case basis what=C2=A0isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0allowed, and then sues people =
who already did it to make them pay big fines.
Now, I sometimes think that these complaints are overstated =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
I think that a lot of crypto projects=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0violate longstand=
ing securities laws, and it=E2=80=99s just wishful thinking to complain abo=
ut a lack of clarity =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I am broadly sympathetic to them. I=
t would probably be better to have clear rules than to have to interpolate =
the rules from backward-looking enforcement actions.
But the way that the SEC actually makes rules is:
=09It writes some rules.=09It proposes them publicly.=09There=E2=80=99s a p=
eriod for industry participants and interested bystanders to submit comment=
s about the rules.=09The SEC considers the comments and puts out final rule=
s.=09Anyone who doesn=E2=80=99t like the rules can sue.=C2=A0 The SEC=E2=80=
=99s authority to regulate crypto (or anything) is contested, and even if i=
t has the authority to regulate, it has to follow proper procedures and not=
 act arbitrarily. Whatever the rules are, you can find arguments against th=
em.=09In 2024, the person who sues=C2=A0will obviously win. The US Supreme =
Court is suspicious of rulemaking by regulatory agencies, but some of the l=
ower courts are=C2=A0way more suspicious, and everybody knows this and can =
bring their lawsuit in a court that will definitely strike down the rules.=
=09And then there is some long appeal process, at the end of which there=E2=
=80=99s a decent chance that the=C2=A0rules will be struck down, and the SE=
C has to go back to the beginning and propose new rules.=09Even this is ove=
rsimplified: Actually different people can sue at different times in differ=
ent courts over different aspects of the rules, leading to even more confus=
ion about what the rules are.

The incentives, for the SEC, are bad. If it makes new rules, that is a lot =
of work, and those rules will be attacked from every angle. Probably they w=
ill be struck down, in ways that limit the SEC=E2=80=99s power and create=
=C2=A0greater=C2=A0confusion about what is allowed.
Meanwhile if the SEC just sees some crypto project that it doesn=E2=80=99t =
like, it can sue that project =E2=80=94=C2=A0probably in a court of=C2=A0it=
s=C2=A0choosing =E2=80=94 say =E2=80=9Cthis violates longstanding securitie=
s law,=E2=80=9D and have a decent chance (not a certainty!) of winning. Its=
 chances are better not only because it can pick a more sympathetic court, =
but also because it can pick a less=C2=A0sympathetic antagonist: It can arg=
ue =E2=80=9Cwe need the power to regulate crypto=E2=80=9D in a case where=
=20
investors lost everything=C2=A0and the value of regulation is clear, rather=
 than writing general rules and getting sued by a nice upstanding firm that=
 doesn=E2=80=99t like them.=C2=A0
And by bringing those cases, it can provide reasonable clarity about (what =
it thinks are) the boundaries of the law. In the case of crypto, the SEC pr=
etty clearly thinks the answer is =E2=80=9Cyou can=E2=80=99t do crypto,=E2=
=80=9D but that is not necessary to this analysis. Even if the SEC were mor=
e sympathetic to crypto, it would probably set out the rules by (1) suing p=
eople who do stuff it doesn=E2=80=99t like and (2) informally advising othe=
r people =E2=80=9Cif you do=C2=A0this=C2=A0stuff, we won=E2=80=99t sue you.=
=E2=80=9D The rules are set by what the SEC sues over=C2=A0and what it does=
n=E2=80=99t sue over, not by actually writing rules.
I don=E2=80=99t think that this is as bad as crypto people say it is =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0this is kind of the normal common-law way that a lot of rules get =
made, and there is some value in having courts, rather than the SEC, decide=
 what is allowed=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but, sure, it's not great. But my poin=
t here is that, even if you do think it=E2=80=99s bad, it=E2=80=99s not ent=
irely the SEC=E2=80=99s fault.
This comes up most often around here about crypto, but it=E2=80=99s not jus=
t about crypto. The current SEC has an=20
ambitious rulemaking agenda and also an=20
ambitious enforcement agenda, but the former is at more risk of=20
being reversed. And it=E2=80=99s not just the SEC. Here=E2=80=99s a Bloombe=
rg Law article by=C2=A0Evan Weinberger titled =E2=80=9CBank Regulators to L=
ean on Enforcement as High Court Hits Rules=E2=80=9D:

A pair of US Supreme Court decisions curtailing the rule-writing authority =
of federal regulators will likely force banking agencies to rely on their s=
upervisory and enforcement powers to police Wall Street.
The high court on Monday ruled that any new entrant to a market has six yea=
rs from the time they=E2=80=99re able to sue to challenge a regulation they=
 oppose, exposing a broad universe of existing rules to new legal fights. T=
hat came just days after the justices overturned a long-standing doctrine d=
eferring to regulators on interpreting ambiguous laws.
The decisions are set to crimp high-profile financial rules, including stri=
cter capital requirements proposed by the Federal Reserve, the Federal Depo=
sit Insurance Corp., and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency.
But unlike other federal regulators, the prudential banking agencies have c=
lear powers to directly supervise banks for unsafe and unsound banking prac=
tices. And those supervisors can force banks to hold more capital or change=
 business practices behind closed doors.
With their authority curbed on the rulemaking front, banking regulators may=
 end up leaning on their supervisory and enforcement tools, said Graham Ste=
ele, the former assistant Treasury secretary for financial institutions in =
the Biden administration.
=E2=80=9CThat is one irony of this whole effort,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CThis could actually lead to regulation by the agencies being more opaque=
, less transparent, and by an examiner-by-examiner basis.=E2=80=9D

By the way, the proper answer to all of this is that=C2=A0Congress=C2=A0has=
 to make detailed explicit rules for crypto, and for anything else that you=
 want regulated.=20
The point of the current Supreme Court=E2=80=99s restrictions on rulemaking=
 is that it wants elected lawmakers in Congress, not bureaucrats at the reg=
ulatory agencies, to make the rules.=C2=A0

