When we last discussed Canna Global, I pointed out that it is not that unco=
mmon for a company to (1) need money, (2) find potential investors who are =
willing to give the company money in exchange for stock, but (3) not have e=
nough stock to give them. That was roughly Canna Global=E2=80=99s situation=
, but it comes up more often when a company=E2=80=99s charter says =E2=80=
=9Cthis company can issue up to 100 million shares,=E2=80=9D or whatever, a=
nd the company has issued 99 million and wants to issue more.
The simplest solution, in that case, is to ask shareholders to vote to amen=
d the charter to authorize more shares. But that takes time, and sometimes =
you need the money now. In that case, the less simple solution is to issue =
some sort of IOU for stock: =E2=80=9CYou give us the money now, and in exch=
ange we=E2=80=99ll promise to give you the stock when we can get shareholde=
rs to authorize it.=E2=80=9D
Usually this IOU takes the form of =E2=80=9Cblank check preferred stock=E2=
=80=9D: The investors get a new special preferred stock (not covered by the=
 charter=E2=80=99s limitation on shares), and the preferred converts into c=
ommon stock whenever the company gets around to amending its charter to aut=
horize more stock.
All of this can be a bit more urgent for=C2=A0banks. A bank is a highly lev=
eraged pile of assets, which means:
=09Its stock can go down a lot. You might think =E2=80=9Cwe have 56 million=
