607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb810e2ba" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
investors lost everything</a>=C2=A0and the value of regulation is clear, ra=
ther than writing general rules and getting sued by a nice upstanding firm =
that doesn=E2=80=99t like them.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And by bringing those cases, it can provide re=
asonable clarity about (what it thinks are) the boundaries of the law. In t=
he case of crypto, the SEC pretty clearly thinks the answer is =E2=80=9Cyou=
 can=E2=80=99t do crypto,=E2=80=9D but that is not necessary to this analys=
is. Even if the SEC were more sympathetic to crypto, it would probably set =
out the rules by (1) suing people who do stuff it doesn=E2=80=99t like and =
(2) informally advising other people =E2=80=9Cif you do=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0=
</em>stuff, we won=E2=80=99t sue you.=E2=80=9D The rules are set by what th=
e SEC sues over=C2=A0and what it doesn=E2=80=99t sue over, not by actually =
writing rules.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that this is as bad as c=
rypto people say it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0this is kind of the normal common-law=
 way that a lot of rules get made, and there is some value in having courts=
, rather than the SEC, decide what is allowed=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but, sure=
, it's not <em>great</em>. But my point here is that, even if you do think =
it=E2=80=99s bad, it=E2=80=99s not entirely the SEC=E2=80=99s fault.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This comes up most often around here about cry=
pto, but it=E2=80=99s not just about crypto. The current SEC has an <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35947004.223415/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlLXNlYy1o=
